        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1970-07-08T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1970-07-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="92"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d92">
                <head>92. Summary of a Verification Panel Meeting<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d92fn1">Source: National Archives, Nixon Presidential Materials,
                            <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Files, <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                            >NSC</gloss> Institutional Files (<gloss target="#t_H1"
                        >H</gloss>-Files), Box <gloss target="#t_H1">H</gloss>–107, Verification
                        Panel Minutes Originals 1969–3/8/72. Top Secret. The summary was prepared by
                        the <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> staff. According to minutes of the
                        meeting, it was held from 3 to 4 p.m. and was attended by: <persName
                            corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_PD1"
                            >Packard</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_FPJ1">Farley</persName>,
                            <persName>Demler</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_HRM1"
                            >Helms</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_SRI1">Spiers</persName>,
                            <persName>Von Ins</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_OPA1"
                            >Odeen</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_MJ1">Martin</persName>,
                            <persName corresp="#p_LLE1">Lynn</persName>,
                            <persName>Slocombe</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_CB1"
                            >Clarke</persName>, and <persName corresp="#p_SH1"
                            >Sonnenfeldt</persName>. (Ibid.) A memorandum for the record and notes
                        on the meeting, both prepared in <gloss target="#t_OSD1">OSD</gloss>, are in
                        the Ford Library, <persName corresp="#p_LMR1">Laird</persName> Papers, Box
                        25, <gloss target="#t_SALT1">SALT</gloss>, Chronological File.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1970-07-08">July 8, 1970</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The Panel discussed four technical issues: <list>
                        <item>—unauthorized missile launches and other acts that could lead to the
                            use of nuclear weapons;<note n="2" xml:id="d92fn2">According to the
                                minutes of the meeting, the members discussed the ways, ranging from
                                bombers, seizure of weapons by an ally, and improper notification by
                                overload circuits, that an unauthorized launch could occur.</note>
                        </item>
                        <item>—missile launches beyond national territory;<note n="3"
                                xml:id="d92fn3">According to the minutes, the members discussed the
                                implications, advantages, and difficulties involved but did not
                                reach any firm conclusions. <persName corresp="#p_KHA1"
                                    >Kissinger</persName> called for further exploration by the
                                Working Group.</note>
                        </item>
                        <item>—mass aircraft launches;<note n="4" xml:id="d92fn4">The members
                                discussed whether the Soviets would need to notify the United States
                                and the converse. They briefly mentioned effects on international
                                flight procedures and B–52 air alerts.</note>
                        </item>
                        <item>—detection of unidentified objects.<note n="5" xml:id="d92fn5">The
                                members discussed the problems with existing warning systems used to
                                detect unidentified objects. On this point and on the proposals
                                generally, <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName> stressed
                                the need to obviate international fears of a <gloss target="#t_US1"
                                    >U.S</gloss>.-Soviet condominium if a proposal on preventing
                                nuclear accidents and provocative attacks were linked to a <gloss
                                    target="#t_SALT1">SALT</gloss> agreement.</note>
                        </item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>With respect to each of these issues, Dr. <persName corresp="#p_KHA1"
                        >Kissinger</persName> raised four questions: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>Which events in the last ten years would have been covered?</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>What communication facilities are required?</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>What is the significance or relevance of the danger that would be
                            controlled?</item>
                        <label>4.</label>
                        <item>What are the main ambiguities in the proposal?<note n="6"
                                xml:id="d92fn6">
                                <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName> directed <persName
                                    corresp="#p_LLE1">Lynn</persName> to have the Working Group
                                examine the questions and prepare a paper for the Verification Panel
                                meeting scheduled for July 15. According to a July 14 covering
                                memorandum to <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName> that
                                sent him materials for the July 15 meeting, <persName
                                    corresp="#p_LLE1">Lynn</persName> explained that, given the
                                short turn-around time, the paper was an inadequate basis for
                                decisions. (National Archives, Nixon Presidential Materials, <gloss
                                    target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Files, <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                                    >NSC</gloss> Institutional Files (<gloss target="#t_H1"
                                    >H</gloss>-Files), Box <gloss target="#t_H1">H</gloss>–005,
                                Verification Panel Meeting—<gloss target="#t_SALT1">SALT</gloss>
                                7/15/70)</note>
                        </item>
                    </list>
                </p>
            </div>
